<HEADLINE>
<P>
47 CERTIFIED MARKETS DOT REGION; 
</P>
<P>
RETAILING: STATE APPROVAL GUARANTEES QUALITY STANDARDS AND THAT A FARMER -- NOT 
A MIDDLEMAN -- IS DOING THE SELLING. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOAN DRAKE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are 47 certified farmers' markets in Southern California -- stretching 
from Santa Maria south to Pacific Beach. Some are farmers' markets in the 
strictest sense, where the sole purpose is the direct sale of farm products. 
Others have expanded the concept to include educational demonstrations, 
entertainment and booths selling prepared foods or nonfood items. 
</P>
<P>
Before a farmer can sell commodities at a certified farmers' market, the county 
agricultural commissioner must check that the farmer actually grows what is 
sold. This inspection guarantees buyers they are purchasing directly from the 
farmer, a family member or employee. 
</P>
<P>
Certification also guarantees the produce meets the same quality and maturity 
standards required for supermarkets. It does, however, exempt the produce from 
normal standards for size and appearance, as well as packing and labeling 
requirements; therefore, some produce in the farmers' markets may vary from 
normal size and might be blemished. 
</P>
<P>
Certified farmers' markets are part of a direct marketing program of the 
California Department of Food and Agriculture. The program offers technical 
assistance to nonprofit organizations, local government agencies and one or 
more certified producers who want to open and operate a certified market. 
</P>
<P>
Here's a list of the markets, divided by county: 
</P>
<P>
