<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: DIET AND CHOLESTEROL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NEIL SOLOMON, Neil Solomon is the author of Sick &amp; Tired of Being Sick 
&amp; Tired, Wynwood Press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I have what to me is a fairly simple question, but I've never seen it 
answered anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
If a person has a high cholesterol level, and his doctor says that he should 
get it down, why not put him on a diet with absolutely no fat in it? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: When I prescribe a diet for a patient who has an elevated serum 
cholesterol level, I have a twofold purpose. The first is to reduce the total 
cholesterol and fat levels. The second is to make certain that the patient 
continues to have a nutritionally adequate diet. Both goals can generally be 
achieved even if the diet includes some fat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
