<P>
ITALIANS SNAP UP CUP CARDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MILAN, Italy 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several American players got a kick out of the card-collecting craze in Italy, 
where youngsters rapidly bought out supplies of World Cup cards. 
</P>
<P>
The most popular cards, naturally, have been those of Italian national team 
players. But cards of former World Cup stars Bobby Charlton of England and 
Socrates of Brazil quickly became collector's items. 
</P>
<P>
Only 5,000 of those cards were produced by MasterCard, for whom Charlton and 
Socrates are working at the World Cup. Fans have offered up to $20 per card and 
many have approached both players for autographed cards, which would increase 
their value significantly. 
</P>
